grows more intense. The issue of living standards has become one of the most urgent challenges for politicians in both Britain and America. 'The squeezed middle' brings together experts from both sides of the Atlantic to ask what the UK can learn from the US. American workers have not benefited from growth for an entire generation - the average American worker earned no more in 2009 than in 1975. Now British workers are undergoing a similar experience. No longer can they assume that when the economy grows their wages will grow with it. This collection brings together for the first time leading economic and policy thinkers to analyse the impact of different policies on those on low-to middle incomes and to explain what lessons the UK can learn from America's 'lost generation'. This timely book is essential reading for everyone concerned about the living standards crisis, an issue which could decide elections as well as shaping the future for millions of working families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCost and standard of livingzGreat Britain. 0aCost and standard of livingzUnited States. 0aLow-income consumersxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aLow-income consumersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWage-price policyzGreat Britain. 0aWage-price policyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aAlakeson, Vidhya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAppelbaum, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarré, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDraut, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGitterman, Daniel P., econtributor.4ctb4https:/